^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717 ^*N|cp||at|A few comments on this hand. Some people would not open 1NT with my hand, lacking stoppers in 2 suits. But, I think any balanced hand with 15-17 is best opened 1NT even if you have a 5 card major because otherwise, your point count is very hard to get across. There is no good rebid if you don't open those hands 1NT. If for example, you open say 1S and pard bids 1N, what do you do?|
PG| ***** 263 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717 ^*N|cp||at|First of all, even if 2N is right, the contract is probably wrong sided and second of all, 2N may be too high if partner has a real weak hand. So, if you open 1N, you get your point count across. The only small danger in opening 1N with a 5 card major is you might miss a 5-3 fit. However, often with a 5-3 fit, 3N does just as well as 4 of the major.Once in a while, it turns out you can only take 9 tricks, even with your 5-3 fit.|
PG| ***** 264 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717 ^*N|cp||at|As far as the play goes once there is a diamond lead, Stan can count 7 tricks. And he wisely took them, because there is some chance if he messes around, he could end up losing 4 or 5 hearts and 3 clubs.|
