^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717 ^*N|cp||at|Okay, the defense made the classic mistake of switching suits. This hand should be down 1 for sure, and possibly down 2. It is hard for Jackie to lead a diamond when she is in, but once she plays a spade, she should continue the suit. By switching between diamonds and spades, you ended up knocking out the defense stoppers in 2 suits and therefore set up 2 extra tricks for Stan. In general, once you start a suit on defense, continue playing it, unless you have  a clear reason not to. And on this hand there was no clear reason. |
PG| ***** 282 ***** |


NT||cp|8|
AT|^B@2^Z@3^*Bhondo717 ^*N|cp||at|In fact, it was pretty clear Stan could not have the King and Queen of spades both because he probably plays a spade at some point if he did. And even if he did have both, once Jackie plays the Ace they are set up anyway, so you might as well continue. The moral of the story is, decide on a defense, and stick to it, unless you have a very good reason that you can articulate to switch.|
